  "response_text": "As a beginner, it's essential to start with a routine that's manageable, enjoyable, and progressive. Here's a suggested fitness routine to get you started:\n\n**Warm-up (5-10 minutes)**\n\n1. Light cardio: Jumping jacks, jogging in place, or cycling\n2. Dynamic stretching: Leg swings, arm circles, and hip circles\n\n**Monday (Upper Body):**\n\n1. Push-ups: 3 sets of 5-8 reps\n2. Bicep curls (using dumbbells or water bottles): 3 sets of 8-12 reps\n3. Tricep dips (using a chair or bench): 3 sets of 8-12 reps\n4. Shoulder press (using dumbbells or water bottles): 3 sets of 8-12 reps\n\n**Tuesday (Lower Body):**\n\n1. Squats: 3 sets of 5-8 reps\n2. Lunges: 3 sets of 8-12 reps (per leg)\n3. Calf raises: 3 sets of 12-15 reps\n4. Leg raises (using a chair or bench): 3 sets of 12-15 reps\n\n**Wednesday (Rest day)**\n\n**Thursday (Core):**\n\n1. Plank: 3 sets of 30-60 seconds\n2. Russian twists (using a medicine ball or weight): 3 sets of 12-15 reps\n3. Leg raises (hanging leg raises or using a bench): 3 sets of 12-15 reps\n4. Bicycle crunches: 3 sets of 12-15 reps\n\n**Friday (Upper Body):**\n\n1. Incline push-ups (using a chair or bench): 3 sets of 5-8 reps\n2. Lateral raises (using dumbbells or water bottles): 3 sets of 8-12 reps\n3. Chest press (using dumbbells or a resistance band): 3 sets of 8-12 reps\n4. Rows (using dumbbells or a resistance band): 3 sets of 8-12 reps\n\n**Saturday and Sunday (Rest days or active recovery)**\n\n**Additional Tips:**\n\n1. Start with lighter weights and progress gradually.\n2. Focus on proper form and technique.\n3. Increase the number of reps or sets as you get stronger.\n4. Listen to your body and rest when needed.\n5. Stay hydrated and fuel your body with a balanced diet.\n6. Aim for 150 minutes of moderate-intensity exercise or 75 minutes of vigorous-intensity exercise per week.\n\n**Remember:**\n\n1. Consult with a healthcare professional before starting any new exercise routine.\n2. It's essential to find a workout routine that you enjoy and can stick to in the long term.\n3. Be patient and celebrate small victories along the way.\n\nAs you progress, you can modify this routine to suit your needs and goals. Remember to stay consistent, and most importantly, have fun!",
